{"title_page": "Sultan Balkhi", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2017}}\n{{Infobox religious biography\n| honorific-prefix = Shah\n| name           = Sultan Balkhi\n| honorific-suffix = Mahisawar\n| image          = Mazar Sharif of Shah Sultan Balkhi Mahisawar.jpg\n| caption        = The [[Mazar (mausoleum)|mazar]] of Mahisawar\n| religion       = [[Islam]]\n| alias          = Bolkhi Mahisowar\n| location       = [[Mahasthangarh]], [[Pundravardhana]]\n| period         = 14th century\n| father         = Shah Ali Asghar Balkhi\n| birth_place    = [[Balkh]], modern-day [[Afghanistan]]\n| death_date     = \n| death_place    = [[Mahasthangarh]], [[Pundravardhana]] (modern-day [[Bogra District|Bogura]], [[Bangladesh]])\n| resting_place  = Mausoleum of Sultan Balkhi, [[Shibganj Upazila, Bogra|Shibganj]], [[Bogra District|Bogra]]\n}}\n'''Shah Sultan Balkhi''' ({{lang-bn|\u09b6\u09be\u09b9 \u09b8\u09c1\u09b2\u09a4\u09be\u09a8 \u09ac\u09b2\u0996\u09c0}}, {{lang-fa|\u0634\u0627\u0647 \u0633\u0644\u0637\u0627\u0646 \u0628\u0644\u062e\u06cc}}), also known by his [[sobriquet]], '''Mahisawar''' ({{lang-bn|\u09ae\u09be\u09b9\u09bf\u09b8\u09be\u0993\u09af\u09bc\u09be\u09b0}}, {{lang-fa|\u0645\u0627\u0647\u06cc \u0633\u0648\u0627\u0631|M\u00e2hi-Sav\u00e2r|Fish-rider}}), was a  14th-century Muslim saint.<ref name=\"forts\">{{cite news|url=http://www.newagebd.com/2008/jan/04/jan04/xtra_also2.html |publisher=New Age |date=January 4, 2008 |accessdate=January 11, 2016 |title=A fort among hundred forts |author=Omar Khalid Rumi |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080108093044/http://www.newagebd.com/2008/jan/04/jan04/xtra_also2.html |archivedate=January 8, 2008 }}</ref> His name is associated with the [[spread of Islam]] in [[Sandwip]] and [[Bogra District|Bogra]].\n\n==Early life==\nBalkhi was the son of Shah Ali Asghar, a ruler of [[Balkh]] in [[Afghanistan]].<ref name=akhter>{{cite book|last=Akhter|first=Fariduddin|title=Tazkeratul Aulia|publisher=Meena Book House|location=[[Dhaka]]|year=2005|pages=252\u2013253}}</ref> He was the [[crown prince]] but left this role to become a follower of the religious preacher, Shaykh Tawfiq of [[Damascus]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Saklayen|first=Ghulam|title=Bangladesher Sufi Sadhak|publisher=[[Islamic Foundation Bangladesh]]|location=[[Dhaka]]|year=2003|page=84}}</ref>\n\n==Migration to Bengal==\nOne day, the Shaykh ordered Balkhi to go to the land of [[Bengal]] and preach the religion of [[Islam]] there. It is said that [[Ibrahim ibn Adham]], another religious figure from Balkh, accompanied him on this journey.<ref name=sen/> Balkhi then set off by boat, eventually reaching the island of [[Sandwip]] where he remained in for a number of years. His boat was a [[barge]] and shaped like a fish; leading to him earning the nickname of Mahi-sawar (fish-rider).<ref name=bpedia>{{cite Banglapedia|article=Shah Sultan Mahisawar (R)|author=Abdul Karim}}</ref> He then went to Hariramnagar, most likely another island, which was ruled by Balaram, a [[Hindu]] Raja who worshipped [[Kali]]. Balaram's minister decided to accept Islam which angered the Raja. A feud took place eventually leading to Balaram's death.\n\nBalkhi then decided to leave Hariramnagar so he leaped on his boat, reaching the ancient city of [[Mahasthangarh]], the capital of the [[Pundravardhana]] kingdom, ruled by Narsingh Parshuram of the Bhoj Garh dynasty.<ref name=sen>{{cite book|title=Bogurar Itihas|language=bn|last=Sen|first=Provash Chandra}}</ref> Balkhi asked Parshuram for permission to live in his domain and freely practice his religion to which the King allowed. Balkhi preached to the native Buddhists and Chilhan, the army chief of Raja Parshuram, amongst many others accepted the message of Islam.<ref name=\"Bogra\"/>  Parshuram, like Balaram, was also not happy with Balkhi's missionary activities and a war took place. Another officer of Parshuram, Harapal, betrayed the king and also became a Muslim.<ref>Mahastan by Dr. Nazimuddin Ahmed. p. 27</ref> This led to Balkhi eventually defeating Parshuram and conquering his fort in 1343.<ref name=forts/><ref name=\"Bogra\">{{ cite web|url=http://bogra.info/history2.html|title=Bogra}}</ref> Parshuram was the last [[Buddhist]] king of [[Mahasthangarh]]. After hearing the news of her father's death, the King's daughter, Princess Shiladevi drowned herself in the [[Karatoya River]]. The area around her drowning place is known as Shila Devi's [[Ghat]].<ref>{{cite Banglapedia|article=Shila Devir Ghat|author=Khan, Ayub}}</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\nIt is unknown how and when Balkhi died. During the reign of [[Mughal emperor]] [[Aurangzeb]] in 1685, the [[dargah]] of Balkhi was a rent-free land and [[Deed#Sanad|sanad]]s were issued to Syed Muhammad Tahir, Syed Abd ar-Rahman and Syed Muhammad Reza.<ref name=bpedia/> The [[Mughal Empire|Mughals]] paid great attention to the shrine and built a gate entry to Balkhi's [[mazar (mausoleum)|mausoleum]] called ''Buri Ka Darwaza''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Mausoleum of Shah Sultan Mahisawar Balkhi|url=https://visitworldheritage.com/en/buddha/mausoleum-of-shah-sultan-mahisawar-balkhi/196207e7-5ac7-4b60-8393-312690b6425f|website=Visit World Heritage}}</ref> In 1719, during the reign of Emperor [[Farrukhsiyar]], Khodadil built a large single-domed mosque near the shrine which remains in use today.<ref>{{cite Banglapedia|article=Mahasthan Mosque|author=Khan, Muhammad Ayoub}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Balkhi Mahisawar}}\n[[Category:History of Islam in Bangladesh]]\n[[Category:Bangladeshi Sufi saints]]\n[[Category:14th-century Muslims]]\n[[Category:People from Balkh Province]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2017}}\n{{Infobox religious biography\n| honorific-prefix = Shah\n| name           = Sultan Balkhi\n| honorific-suffix = Mahisawar\n| image          = Mazar Sharif of Shah Sultan Balkhi Mahisawar.jpg\n| caption        = The [[Mazar (mausoleum)|mazar]] of Mahisawar\n| religion       = [[Islam]]\n| alias          = Bolkhi Mahisowar\n| location       = [[Mahasthangarh]], [[Pundravardhana]]\n| period         = 14th century\n| father         = Shah Ali Asghar Balkhi\n| birth_place    = [[Balkh]], modern-day [[Afghanistan]]\n| death_date     = \n| death_place    = [[Mahasthangarh]], [[Pundravardhana]] (modern-day [[Bogra District|Bogura]], [[Bangladesh]])\n| resting_place  = Mausoleum of Sultan Balkhi, [[Shibganj Upazila, Bogra|Shibganj]], [[Bogra District|Bogra]]\n}}\n'''Shah Sultan Balkhi''' ({{lang-bn|\u09b6\u09be\u09b9 \u09b8\u09c1\u09b2\u09a4\u09be\u09a8 \u09ac\u09b2\u0996\u09c0}}, {{lang-fa|\u0634\u0627\u0647 \u0633\u0644\u0637\u0627\u0646 \u0628\u0644\u062e\u06cc}}), also known by his [[sobriquet]], '''Mahisawar''' ({{lang-bn|\u09ae\u09be\u09b9\u09bf\u09b8\u09be\u0993\u09af\u09bc\u09be\u09b0}}, {{lang-fa|\u0645\u0627\u0647\u06cc \u0633\u0648\u0627\u0631|M\u00e2hi-Sav\u00e2r|Fish-rider}}), was a  14th-century Muslim saint.<ref name=\"forts\">{{cite news|url=http://www.newagebd.com/2008/jan/04/jan04/xtra_also2.html |publisher=New Age |date=January 4, 2008 |accessdate=January 11, 2016 |title=A fort among hundred forts |author=Omar Khalid Rumi |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080108093044/http://www.newagebd.com/2008/jan/04/jan04/xtra_also2.html |archivedate=January 8, 2008 }}</ref> His name is associated with the [[spread of Islam]] in [[Sandwip]] and [[Bogra District|Bogra]].\n\n==Early life==\nBalkhi was the son of Shah Ali Asghar, a ruler of [[Balkh]] in [[Afghanistan]].<ref name=akhter>{{cite book|last=Akhter|first=Fariduddin|title=Tazkeratul Aulia|publisher=Meena Book House|location=[[Dhaka]]|year=2005|page=252-253}}</ref> He was the [[crown prince]] but left this role to become a follower of the religious preacher, Shaykh Tawfiq of [[Damascus]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Saklayen|first=Ghulam|title=Bangladesher Sufi Sadhak|publisher=[[Islamic Foundation Bangladesh]]|location=[[Dhaka]]|year=2003|page=84}}</ref>.\n\n==Migration to Bengal==\nOne day, the Shaykh ordered Balkhi to go to the land of [[Bengal]] and preach the religion of [[Islam]] there. It is said that [[Ibrahim ibn Adham]], another religious figure from Balkh, accompanied him on this journey.<ref name=sen/> Balkhi then set off by boat, eventually reaching the island of [[Sandwip]] where he remained in for a number of years. His boat was a [[barge]] and shaped like a fish; leading to him earning the nickname of Mahi-sawar (fish-rider).<ref name=bpedia>{{cite Banglapedia|article=Shah Sultan Mahisawar (R)|author=Abdul Karim}}</ref> He then went to Hariramnagar, most likely another island, which was ruled by Balaram, a [[Hindu]] Raja who worshipped [[Kali]]. Balaram's minister decided to accept Islam which angered the Raja. A feud took place eventually leading to Balaram's death.\n\nBalkhi then decided to leave Hariramnagar so he leaped on his boat, reaching the ancient city of [[Mahasthangarh]], the capital of the [[Pundravardhana]] kingdom, ruled by Narsingh Parshuram of the Bhoj Garh dynasty.<ref name=sen>{{cite book|title=Bogurar Itihas|language=bn|last=Sen|first=Provash Chandra}}</ref> Balkhi asked Parshuram for permission to live in his domain and freely practice his religion to which the King allowed. Balkhi preached to the native Buddhists and Chilhan, the army chief of Raja Parshuram, amongst many others accepted the message of Islam.<ref name=\"Bogra\"/>  Parshuram, like Balaram, was also not happy with Balkhi's missionary activities and a war took place. Another officer of Parshuram, Harapal, betrayed the king and also became a Muslim.<ref>Mahastan by Dr. Nazimuddin Ahmed. p. 27</ref> This led to Balkhi eventually defeating Parshuram and conquering his fort in 1343.<ref name=forts/><ref name=\"Bogra\">{{ cite web|url=http://bogra.info/history2.html|title=Bogra}}</ref> Parshuram was the last [[Buddhist]] king of [[Mahasthangarh]]. After hearing the news of her father's death, the King's daughter, Princess Shiladevi drowned herself in the [[Karatoya River]]. The area around her drowning place is known as Shila Devi's [[Ghat]].<ref>{{cite Banglapedia|article=Shila Devir Ghat|author=Khan, Ayub}}</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\nIt is unknown how and when Balkhi died. During the reign of [[Mughal emperor]] [[Aurangzeb]] in 1685, the [[dargah]] of Balkhi was a rent-free land and [[Deed#Sanad|sanad]]s were issued to Syed Muhammad Tahir, Syed Abd ar-Rahman and Syed Muhammad Reza.<ref name=bpedia/> The [[Mughal Empire|Mughals]] payed great attention to the shrine and built a gate entry to Balkhi's [[mazar (mausoleum)|mausoleum]] called ''Buri Ka Darwaza''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Mausoleum of Shah Sultan Mahisawar Balkhi|url=https://visitworldheritage.com/en/buddha/mausoleum-of-shah-sultan-mahisawar-balkhi/196207e7-5ac7-4b60-8393-312690b6425f|website=Visit World Heritage}}</ref> In 1719, during the reign of Emperor [[Farrukhsiyar]], Khodadil built a large single-domed mosque near the shrine which remains in use today.<ref>{{cite Banglapedia|article=Mahasthan Mosque|author=Khan, Muhammad Ayoub}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Balkhi Mahisawar}}\n[[Category:History of Islam in Bangladesh]]\n[[Category:Bangladeshi Sufi saints]]\n[[Category:14th-century Muslims]]\n[[Category:People from Balkh Province]]\n", "name_user": "John of Reading", "label": "safe", "comment": "Typo/generalfixes, replaced: payed \u2192 paid", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sultan_Balkhi"}
